  "footnotes": [
    "Pyu city-states (c.200 BCE–1050 CE): the earliest urban civilization in Burma; the Pyu were Tibeto-Burman speakers who practiced Theravada Buddhism, Hinduism, and indigenous religions; their cities (Sri Ksetra, Halin, Beikthano) are UNESCO World Heritage sites; the Nanzhao raids of 832 devastated Halin and weakened Pyu power",
    "Pagan Kingdom (1044–1297): Anawrahta unified Burma and adopted Theravada Buddhism from the Mon, building thousands of temples at Bagan; at its peak it was one of the largest cities in the world; Mongol pressure (not a full conquest) contributed to its fragmentation after 1287",
    "Mrauk U kingdom (1430–1785): the Arakanese golden age; Mrauk U was a cosmopolitan port kingdom trading with the Portuguese, Mughals, and Dutch; it issued trilingual coins (Arakanese, Persian, Portuguese); its conquest by the Konbaung dynasty in 1785 triggered the Rohingya diaspora's earliest modern phase",
    "Konbaung dynasty (1752–1885): founded by Alaungpaya, it was the last Burmese dynasty; Bayinnaung-like in ambition, it conquered Arakan, Manipur, and Assam, provoking British India; the three Anglo-Burmese Wars (1824, 1852, 1885) progressively dismembered the kingdom until total annexation",
    "Shan states: the Shan (Tai) peoples established numerous principalities (mong) across the highlands of eastern Burma from the 13th century; they were never fully integrated into lowland Burmese kingdoms; the Panglong Agreement (1947) promised autonomy but was never honored, fueling decades of ethnic insurgency",
    "Japanese occupation (1942–1945): Japan conquered Burma in early 1942, establishing the nominally independent State of Burma under Ba Maw; Aung San initially collaborated but switched sides in 1945; the Burma Road (connecting China to Allied supply lines) made Burma a critical WWII theater",
    "2021 coup and civil war: the Tatmadaw (military) overthrew Aung San Suu Kyi's NLD government on 1 February 2021; mass protests were met with lethal force; the National Unity Government (NUG) and People's Defence Forces (PDF) launched armed resistance; the ongoing civil war has displaced millions and fragmented the country along ethnic lines"
  ]
